---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
import neovim from "../assets/Neovim-logo.png";
import ghostty from "../assets/ghostty_logo.jpg";
import opencode from "../assets/opencode-wordmark-dark.svg";
import tmux from "../assets/Tmux_logo.png";
---

<Layout>
	<article class="flex flex-col items-center gap-4">
		<h2 class="self-start">Terminal:</h2>
		<p>
			I tend to use the terminal for most of my development workflow. These are
			some of the things I use on a daily basis in order to be as efficient as
			possible.
		</p>
		<ul class="list-disc flex flex-col gap-6">
			<img src={neovim.src} class="h-20 w-64 self-center">
			<li>
				<a
					href="#"
					class="text-blue-400 underline cursor-pointer hover:text-blue-600"
				>
					Neovim
				</a>
				has been my main editor for almost 2 years. It has an incredibly high
				learning curve but once you've mastered vim motions and gained some
				understanding of the underlying processes it is a fantastic development
				experience.
			</li>

			<img src={tmux.src} class="h-20 w-64 self-center">
			<li>TMUX</li>

			<img src={opencode.src} class="h-20 w-64 self-center">
			<li>opencode</li>

			<!-- <img src={ghostty.src} class="h-32 w-40 self-center"> -->
		</ul>
		Neovim Tmux Both of these tools require a fair amount of configuration. If
		you're curious how I set mine up or you're looking for a jumping off point,
		you can take a look at my dotfiles. I keep them pretty up-to-date for my own
		use when setting up new machines. LINK TO DOTFILES
	</article>
</Layout>
